(26, 343, 'Narapron', '', 'http://sYr5PfGGRB9', '85.133.23.227', '2013-10-02 19:13:23', '2013-10-02 19:13:23', 'Consider specifying wehethr you''d like comments on youtube or your blog. What is the most important change in American society, ideology, policy etc. that you find necessary in resolving inequality? Self perpetuating class is not a big secret, and the American Dream has already been proclaimed dead by many.Ideology is indeed the most dangerous aspect of blocking upward mobility. Mentality is also a big aspect of being rich or poor. As you said, these mentalities are passed from one generation to the next.  In light of this, what is supposed to change the mentality of the rich AND poor? I emphasize  and'', because there is this vindictiveness towards rich people. In the way we consider the underprivileged victims of their status, many rich are in the same boat. Rich who are stout republicans in the pursuit to keep their money are much like the poor abusing welfare in this sense. We don''t agree with it, but its their prerogative to utilize the resources given to them. This is another thing, proposing change in American policy to change the ideologies of American people sounds like a dangerous idea. Maybe you point out that there are greater repercussions for the irresponsibility of the rich, so it is necessary to minimize the potentially bad ones. Again, success is a mentality. You will commonly find a constant sense of entitlement. I''ll have to find the sources, but this is a huge aspect of  the successful.  It ties into the danger in the poor thinking they deserve it. The rich think they deserve it too. So, this similar trait of entitlement is a flaw in the poor, yet a necessary characteristic for the rich. We can''t forget how much of this stems from practicality. I could go on but there''s already a lot that could be discussed. Is a boundless sense of entitlement assumed by the rich to be in the poor? Is this why they may think the poor are less able? Or do they correctly think it isn''t, but attribute that to laziness? Can policy change minds, or is there a need for a great social change of some kind? Will the soon-coming rise of the least religious, existentialist, narcissistic generation of ours see major changes to American culture in either direction (of good or bad)? 8888', 0, '0', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64; rv:19.0) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/19.0', '', 0, 0),
