(374, 1, '2013-08-15 16:25:13', '2013-08-15 16:25:13', '<h3 dir="ltr">Community Immersion-Customer Development</h3>\r\n<a href="http://startupscholarship.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/EntrepreneursBreak_a.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-276" alt="EntrepreneursBreak_a" src="http://startupscholarship.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/EntrepreneursBreak_a.png" /><a href="http://startupscholarship.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/The-Startup-Scholarship-Logo-WhiteLet+GreyBack-copy-copy.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-198" alt="The Startup Scholarship Logo (WhiteLet+GreyBack) copy copy" src="http://startupscholarship.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/The-Startup-Scholarship-Logo-WhiteLet+GreyBack-copy-copy.png" /></a></a>\r\n<p dir="ltr">In the sunny week of August we had another workshop by Entrepreneurs Break (EB). After delivering workshops on Lean Canvas + Idea Generation (Pedro Carmo Oliveira) and Prototyping + User Experience (Paulo Fonseca), Pedro Carmo Oliveira returned to introduce us to the Customer Development methodology.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://startupscholarship.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/63694_10153115334940716_638885366_n.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-370" alt="63694_10153115334940716_638885366_n" src="http://startupscholarship.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/63694_10153115334940716_638885366_n.jpg" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">With his usual energy and informality, Pedro started by describing his past experiences with startups, more specifically with “My CV Map”, “Oops Booking” and “Mr. Map”, all startups that for one reason or another did not explode. Some would call them a failure. We call them learning experiences.  Perhaps due to this, Pedro does not stop believing and is starting a new startup in the HR field called Muchowork.com and we’ll be around to see how it goes.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">Before starting with the theoretical side of customer dev, Pedro did a very practical exercise by asking what the scholars thought of the tagline he uses to describe himself on different websites. Scholars were honest and pretty much questioned everything.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">From there we were taken through the intricacies of customer development. What are the questions you should ask and the way you should ask them? Is asking how much a potential customer would pay for the product or service a good question? What about asking the customers if what you are developing is a good idea? Well, perhaps those are bad questions as they stretch too much the customer’s imagination. Questions that focus on understanding the customer’s problems and how she currently solves it go in the right direction according to the customer development methodology.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">To finalize the workshop, Pedro gave a series of useful tools to apply the customer dev technology.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">Entrepreneurs Break is a community of non-bullshit entrepreneurs that provides you with awesome startup tools and insights.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">Pedro Conceição, Founder of Kairos Society Portugal</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr"></p>\r\n\r\n<h1></h1>', '', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '367-revision-6', '', '', '2013-08-15 16:25:13', '2013-08-15 16:25:13', '', 367, 'http://startupscholarship.org/blog/367-revision-6/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
